      "sanskrit": "sthitā pratiṣṭhitā aham asmi paraṃ brahma iti prajñā yasya saḥ sthita-prajñas tasya sthita-prajñasya kā bhāṣā kiṃ bhāṣaṇaṃ vacanaṃ katham asau parair bhāṣyate samādhi-sthasya samādhau sthitasya he keśava | sthita-dhīḥ sthita-prajñaḥ svayaṃ vā kiṃ prabhāṣeta | kim āsīta vrajeta kim āsanaṃ vrajanaṃ vā tasya katham ity arthaḥ | sthita-prajñasya lakṣaṇam anena lokena pṛcchayate",
      "ourRendering": "‘sthitā’ means firmly established: he whose prajñā (prajñā) ‘I am Brahman, the Supreme’ is firmly fixed is the man of settled wisdom. What is the ‘speech’ (bhāṣā) of such a one — what saying, what utterance? How is he described by others? — of one settled in samādhi, established in absorption, O Keśava. Or what does the steady-minded man of settled wisdom himself say? How does he sit, how does he move — what is his sitting, his walking, or how is it with him? — that is the meaning. The marks of the man of settled wisdom are asked by this verse.",
