      "locus": "2.64",
      "sanskrit": "rāga-dveṣa-viyuktai rāgaś ca dveṣaś ca rāga-dveṣau, tat-puraḥsarā hi indriyāṇāṃ pravṛttiḥ svābhāvikī, tatra yo mumukṣuḥ bhavati saḥ tābhyāṃ viyuktaiḥ śrotrādibhir indriyair viṣayān avarjanīyān caran upalabhamānaḥ ātma-vaśyair ātmano vaśyāni vaśībhūtāni indriyāṇi tair ātma-vaśyair vidheyātmā icchātaḥ vidheya ātmā antaḥ-karaṇaṃ yasya so 'yaṃ prasādam adhigacchati | prasādaḥ prasannatā svāsthyam",
      "ourRendering": "‘With rāga and dveṣa gone’ — rāga and dveṣa, the rāga-and-dveṣa pair; the engagement of the senses is natural, indeed preceded by them. There, the one who is a seeker of release becomes — by senses, hearing and the rest, freed of those two, ranging over the unavoidable objects, apprehending them, by senses under the Self’s control (the Self’s own controllable ones, the senses that have become subject) — he whose inner organ is governable at will: governable is the self, the inner organ, of whom — he, this one, attains serenity. ‘Serenity’ is clearness, well-being.",
