      "work": "Subodhinī",
      "locus": "2.66",
      "sanskrit": "indriya-nigrahasya sthita-prajñatā-sādhanatvaṃ vyatireka-mukhenopapādayati nāstīti | ayuktasya avaśī-kṛtendriyasya nāsti buddhiḥ | śāstrācāryopadeśābhyām ātma-viṣayā buddhiḥ prajñaiva notpadyate | kutas tasyāḥ pratiṣṭhā-vārtā | kuta ity atrāha na ceti | na cāyuktasya bhāvanā dhyānam | bhāvanayā hi buddher ātmani pratiṣṭhā bhavati, sā ca ayuktasya yato nāsti | na cābhāvayataḥ ātma-dhyānam akurvataḥ śāntiḥ ātmani cittoparamaḥ | aśāntasya kutaḥ sukham mokṣānanda ity arthaḥ ||66||",
      "ourRendering": "He establishes, by way of the negative, that restraint of the senses is the means to the state of settled wisdom, by ‘nāsti’. For the unsteadied one, whose senses are unmastered, there is no understanding: the understanding whose object is the Self, the very prajñā, born of the teaching of scripture and teacher, does not arise. Whence, then, of it, any talk of standing firm? To this ‘whence’ He says ‘na ca’: nor for the unsteadied one is there contemplation, meditation; for it is by contemplation that the understanding’s firmness in the Self comes to be, and that, since it does not exist for the unsteadied one. Nor for the one not making meditation on the Self, the non-contemplating one, is there peace, the ceasing of the mind in the Self. For the unpeaceful one, whence pleasure, the bliss of liberation — that is the meaning.",
      "source": "data/sources/sanskrit/vedanta/gretil_bhg4comm_ch2.txt (GRETIL: gretil/1_sanskr/2_epic/mbh/ext/bhg4c02u.htm)",
