      "locus": "2.67",
      "sanskrit": "nāsti buddhir ayuktasya [Gītā 2.66] ity atra hetum āha indriyāṇām iti | indriyāṇām avaśīkṛtānāṃ svairaṃ viṣayeṣu caratāṃ madhye yadaivaikam indriyaṃ mano 'nuvidhīyate |vaśīkṛtaṃ sad-indriyeṇa saha gacchati, tadaivaikam indriyasya manasaḥ puruṣasya vā prajñāṃ buddhiṃ harati viṣaya-vikṣiptāṃ karoti | kim uta vaktavyaṃ bahūni prajñāṃ harantīti | yathā pramattasya karṇadhārasya nāvaṃ vāyuḥ sarvataḥ paribhramayati tadvad iti ||67||",
      "ourRendering": "To ‘there is no understanding for the unsteadied one’ He gives the cause by ‘indriyāṇām’. Of the senses, unmastered, ranging at will in objects, when even one single sense the mind ‘follows after’ — mastered, goes along with that sense — then that one sense robs the prajñā, the understanding, of the mind or of the man, makes it scattered toward objects. How much more is to be said when many rob the prajñā! Just as the wind whirls about on every side the boat of a careless helmsman — so it is.",
      "source": "data/sources/sanskrit/vedanta/gretil_bhg4comm_ch2.txt (GRETIL: gretil/1_sanskr/2_epic/mbh/ext/bhg4c02u.htm)",
