      "sanskrit": "hi yasmād evaṃ tasmād iti | sarvaśaḥ sarvāṇi samanaskāni | he mahābāho iti sambodhayan sarva-śatru-nivāraṇa-kṣamatvād indriya-śatru-nivāraṇe 'pi tvaṃ kṣamo 'sīti sūcayati | spaṣṭam anyat | tasyeti siddhasya sādhakasya ca parāmarśaḥ | indriya-saṃyamasya sthita-prajñaṃ prati lakṣaṇatvasya mumukṣuṃ prati prajñā-sādhanatvasya copasaṃharaṇīyatvāt ||68||",
      "ourRendering": "‘hi’ (since) — since it is thus, ‘therefore’. From every side, all of them, together with the mind. Addressing him ‘O mighty-armed’, He hints: since you are able to ward off every foe, you are able also to ward off the foe that is the senses. The rest is clear. ‘Of him’ is a reference to both the accomplished one and the aspirant, since the reining-in of the senses — being, with respect to the man of settled wisdom, a defining mark, and, with respect to the seeker of release, a means to prajñā — is to be drawn together into a conclusion.",
      "source": "data/sources/sanskrit/vedanta/gretil_bhg4comm_ch2.txt (GRETIL: gretil/1_sanskr/2_epic/mbh/ext/bhg4c02u.htm)",
