      "voiceId": "sridhara",
      "author": "Śrīdhara Svāmī",
      "school": "Bhakti / Advaita",
      "work": "Subodhinī",
      "locus": "2.72",
      "sanskrit": "uktāṃ jñāna-niṣṭhāṃ stuvann upasaṃharati eṣeti | brāhmī sthitir brahma-jñāna-niṣṭhā | eṣaivaṃvidhā | enāṃ parameśvarārādhanena viśuddhāntaḥkaraṇaḥ pumān prāpya na vimuhyati | punaḥ saṃsāra-mohaṃ na prāpnoti | yato 'nta-kāle mṛtyu-samaye 'py asyāṃ lakṣa-mātram api sthitvā brahma-nirvāṇam brahmaṇi nirvāṇaṃ layam ṛcchati prāpnoti | kiṃ punar vaktavyaṃ bālyam ārabhya sthitvā prāpnotīti ||72|| śoka-paṅka-nimagnaṃ yaḥ sāṅkhya-yogopadeśataḥ | ujjahārārjunaṃ bhaktaṃ sa kṛṣṇa-śaraṇaṃ mama || iti śrī-śrīdhara-svāmikṛtāyāṃ bhagavad-gītā-ṭīkāyāṃ subodhinyāṃ dvitīyo 'dhyāyaḥ ||2||",
      "ourRendering": "Praising the steadfastness in jñāna that was stated, He sums up by ‘eṣā’. The ‘Brahman-state’ is the standing that is steadfastness in the knowledge of Brahman; such is ‘this’, of just this kind. Attaining it, the man whose inner organ is purified by the worship of the Supreme Lord is not deluded; he does not again attain the delusion of saṃsāra. Since, at the final time, the time of death, having abided in it even for a mere instant, he reaches, attains, brahma-nirvāṇa — the blowing-out in Brahman, dissolution; how much more is to be said of one who attains it having abided from childhood on — so. He who, by the teaching of Sāṅkhya and Yoga, lifted up his devotee Arjuna sunk in the mire of grief — that Kṛṣṇa is the refuge that is mine. Thus here ends, in the Subodhinī, the gloss on the Bhagavad-gītā composed by Śrī Śrīdhara Svāmin, the second chapter.",
